target.bio: Earth goddess who tried to kill Coatlicue. Her head was tossed in the sky by his brother, Huitzilopochtli, and became the moon, which represent cowardice for Aztecs..

source.name: Huitzilopochtli
source.bio: God of war, thunderstorms, fire and sun. He's the original deity of the nomadic tribe of Mexica, also known as Aztecs. He was a warrior who need blood to win his battle against darkness.

target.name: Coatlicue
target.bio: Creator goddess of earth, fire, stars of the southern sky and birth. Depicted as a woman wearing a skirt of snakes, with sharp claws, as she was thirsty for sacrifices. Mother of Huitzilopochtli, she's also the inspiration of the weeping woman in mexican folklore.

source.name: Huixtocihuatl
source.bio: Fertility goddess of ocean who discovered salt. Could be a daughter or an aspect of Chalchiuhtlicue

target.name: Tlaloc
target.bio: Main aztec god, with Huitzilopochtli, who controls rain, hurricanes, fertility and lightning. He's also associated with springs, mountains and caves. Babies were drown to give him power.

source.name: Huixtocihuatl
source.bio: Fertility goddess of ocean who discovered salt. Could be a daughter or an aspect of Chalchiuhtlicue

target.name: Chalchiuhtlicue
target.bio: Goddess of water, especially running streams, lakes and ocean. Married to Tlaloc (who control the rain from the sky), she's also a patron of birth

source.name: Huixtocihuatl
source.bio: Fertility goddess of ocean who discovered salt. Could be a daughter or an aspect of Chalchiuhtlicue

target.name: Xochiquetzal
target.bio: Goddess of female sexuality, prostitutes, homosexuals, young mothers, flowers, pleasure and craft (embroiders, weavers, silversmiths and sculptors)

source.name: Huixtocihuatl
source.bio: Fertility goddess of ocean who discovered salt. Could be a daughter or an aspect of Chalchiuhtlicue

target.name: Xilonen
target.bio: Local vegetation goddess, associated with corn. She's an aspect of the maize goddess Chicomecoatl, personifying the weet and young maize plant.

source.name: Ilamacihuatl
source.bio: Lady of Creation. Goddess of weavers, her roar signalled war. She's the elderly version of Chicomecoatl and associated with earth, death, and the milky way

target.name: Ilamatecuhtli
target.bio: Lord of Creation. Another nagual of Ometecuhtli

source.name: Ilamatecuhtli
source.bio: Lord of Creation. Another nagual of Ometecuhtli

target.name: Ilamacihuatl
target.bio: Lady of Creation. Goddess of weavers, her roar signalled war. She's the elderly version of Chicomecoatl and associated with earth, death, and the milky way

source.name: Itzaccihuatl
source.bio: Representation of the great white mountain Iztactepetl, she's a mountain goddess, guardian of animals needed for food. Mexica affected by blindness would worship her.

target.name: Tlaloque
target.bio: Minor water-rain gods and servants of Tlaloc, which brought different kind of rain. They are also associated with mountains.

source.name: Itztapaltotec
source.bio: Minor god of Agriculture and fertility, nagual of Xipe Totec, but also a patron of precious metallurgists. He's probably related to Itztli, who is also depicted as a personified knife.

target.name: Itzpapalotl
target.bio: Aztec goddess of sacrifice, associated with earth and fertility, who rules Tomoanchan, and leader of Cihuateteo and Tzitzimime. Her nahual is the butterfly, a manifestation of the dead souls

source.name: Itztlacoliuhqui
source.bio: Blind god of justice and punishment, associated with stone, cold and obsidian. Associated with night and north, he's a variant of Tezcatllipoca.

target.name: Tlahuizcalpantecuhtli
target.bio: Destructive god of the Morning Star, dawn and east. An aspect of Quetzalcoatl which lives in Mictlan. By way of anecdote, he has the longest name in aztec pantheon.

source.name: Itztlacoliuhqui
source.bio: Blind god of justice and punishment, associated with stone, cold and obsidian. Associated with night and north, he's a variant of Tezcatllipoca.

target.name: Centeotl
target.bio: Olmec, Totonac and mayan god of fertility. Gender-fluid entity revered by maize farmers but also midwives.

source.name: Itztli
source.bio: God of sacrifice and the sacred obsidian stone knives used for ritual slaying. Servant of Tezcatlipoca

target.name: Ixquimilli
target.bio: God of darkness, justice and punishment. Protectors of the sorcereres., he was linked to both Itztlacoliuhqui and Tezcatlipoca.

source.name: Ixnextli
source.bio: Goddess of weavers and aspect of Xochiquetzal when she was exepelled from paradise.

target.name: Huehuecoyotl
target.bio: Trickster and shapeshifter god, associated both with wildness and wisdom, lust and arts, especially dance and music. He was also a guide in Mictlan.

source.name: Ixquimilli

source.name: Malinalxochi
source.bio: Underworld sorceress or goddess of snakes, scorpions and insects of the desert. Trying to slow down the journey of his half brother, Huiztilopochtli, and his people, she's abandonned and founded the city of Malinalco.

target.name: Huitzilopochtli
target.bio: God of war, thunderstorms, fire and sun. He's the original deity of the nomadic tribe of Mexica, also known as Aztecs. He was a warrior who need blood to win his battle against darkness.

source.name: Malinalxochi
source.bio: Underworld sorceress or goddess of snakes, scorpions and insects of the desert. Trying to slow down the journey of his half brother, Huiztilopochtli, and his people, she's abandonned and founded the city of Malinalco.

target.name: Centzon Huitznahua
target.bio: Southern star gods. With Coyolxauhqui, their sister, they tried to kill their mother, Coatlicue. Huitzilipochtli massacred them, symbolising the sunrise and the disappearance of the stars.

source.name: Mayahuel
source.bio: Goddess of the maguay plant and all his by-products, especially pulque. Said to have 400 breasts to nurture her children, she gave love to manking with her romance with Quetzalcoatl.

target.name: Tlazolteotl
target.bio: Goddess of purification from filth, disease or excess, of sin, love, sex, regret and lamentation. She can turn into four aspects, a young moon, cruel and delightful, a sensual young woman, a priestess who bless married couples and a monster who destroy lovers and steal fortune.

source.name: Mayahuel

source.name: Metztli
source.bio: Lowly god of darkness and worms who failed to sacrifice himslef to become the sun and, instead, became the moon.

target.name: Coyolxauhqui
target.bio: Earth goddess who tried to kill Coatlicue. Her head was tossed in the sky by his brother, Huitzilopochtli, and became the moon, which represent cowardice for Aztecs..

source.name: Mictlancihuatl
source.bio: Mistress to Mictlantecuhtli and ruler of the deepest level of Mictlan. She was sacrified as a baby and magically grew to addulthood in the underworld.

target.name: Omecihuatl
target.bio: Female representation of the creator god Ometeotl. God of the near and the distant, of substance and duality, she was mainly revered by the high classes, especially in poetry.

source.name: Mictlantecuhtli
source.bio: God of death and lord of Mictlan, the main Aztec underworld. Living in complete darkness, he guard the bones of dead people but also babies before their birth.

target.name: Xiuhtecuhtli
target.bio: God of fire and time, protector of kings, warriors and pochtecas. One of the oldest cult in aztec mythology. He's also deeply conected with birth.

source.name: Nanahuatzin
source.bio: Lowly goddess who sacrified herself, by jumping into a fire, to become the sun god Tonatiuh. She represented self-sacrifice and courage.

target.name: Tecciztecatl
target.bio: Other name for Metztli. As the god of snails and worms, he failed to sacrifice himself to become the sun and was trasnformed into the moon. Symbol of cowardice.

source.name: Nanahuatzin
source.bio: Lowly goddess who sacrified herself, by jumping into a fire, to become the sun god Tonatiuh. She represented self-sacrifice and courage.

target.name: Xolotl
target.bio: Canine companion and/or twin brother of Quetzalcoatl. God of twins, fire, sickness, deformity and bad luck, he accompanied the dead to Mictlan and nourrished the first men of the fifth sun.

source.name: Nappatecuhtli
source.bio: One of the Tlaloques (water gods), who invented the art of making mats, seats and cane screens with reed, sedge and canes.

target.name: Centzon Totochtin
target.bio: Gods of pulque, drunknness and fertility, known for their frequent parties. There 400 of them, a synonym of infinity.

source.name: Popocatepetl
source.bio: Sacred volcano whose cult worshiped the earth, rain, water, and vegetation. Once a man, he was called away to war but his lover, Iztaccihuatl, died of grief. They ended up transformed into mourning mountains by the Gods.

target.name: Mayahuel
target.bio: Goddess of the maguay plant and all his by-products, especially pulque. Said to have 400 breasts to nurture her children, she gave love to manking with her romance with Quetzalcoatl.

source.name: Quetzalcoatl
source.bio: One of the main divinity worshipped in Mesoamerica. He's  the god of agriculture, arts, love science and wind. Exiled by his brother Tezcatlipoca, his expected return has been seen, at first, as the arrival of Hernan Cortez in 1519.

target.name: Ehecatl
target.bio: Nagual of Quetzalcoatl which represents the west winds that bring rain. His breath helped to move the sun.

source.name: Quetzalcoatl
source.bio: One of the main divinity worshipped in Mesoamerica. He's  the god of agriculture, arts, love science and wind. Exiled by his brother Tezcatlipoca, his expected return has been seen, at first, as the arrival of Hernan Cortez in 1519.

target.name: Tlaloc
target.bio: Main aztec god, with Huitzilopochtli, who controls rain, hurricanes, fertility and lightning. He's also associated with springs, mountains and caves. Babies were drown to give him power.

source.name: Quetzalcoatl
source.bio: One of the main divinity worshipped in Mesoamerica. He's  the god of agriculture, arts, love science and wind. Exiled by his brother Tezcatlipoca, his expected return has been seen, at first, as the arrival of Hernan Cortez in 1519.

target.name: Tonatiuh
target.bio: Sun god, protector of the warriors and symbolized by the eagle, he presides the fifth (and actual) world age. The gods sacrificed themselves to create him and men has to give him enough energy, through blood, to battle against darkness.

source.name: Quetzalcoatl
source.bio: One of the main divinity worshipped in Mesoamerica. He's  the god of agriculture, arts, love science and wind. Exiled by his brother Tezcatlipoca, his expected return has been seen, at first, as the arrival of Hernan Cortez in 1519.

source.name: Quetzalcoatl
source.bio: One of the main divinity worshipped in Mesoamerica. He's  the god of agriculture, arts, love science and wind. Exiled by his brother Tezcatlipoca, his expected return has been seen, at first, as the arrival of Hernan Cortez in 1519.

target.name: Tezcatlipoca
target.bio: Omnipotent god of rulers, sorcerers or warriors, he rules night, death, discord, conflict, temptation, change and destruction. Symbolised by the jaguar, he's a rival of Quetzalcoatl and one of the most complex aztec god.

source.name: Quetzalcoatl
source.bio: One of the main divinity worshipped in Mesoamerica. He's  the god of agriculture, arts, love science and wind. Exiled by his brother Tezcatlipoca, his expected return has been seen, at first, as the arrival of Hernan Cortez in 1519.

target.name: Xipe Totec
target.bio: Fierce god of agriculture, fertility, seasons and renewal, he was also a protector of gold workers, jewelers and warriors. He flayed himself to give humanity food, and was shown as wearing a flayed human skin

source.name: Quetzalcoatl
source.bio: One of the main divinity worshipped in Mesoamerica. He's  the god of agriculture, arts, love science and wind. Exiled by his brother Tezcatlipoca, his expected return has been seen, at first, as the arrival of Hernan Cortez in 1519.

target.name: Azcatl

target.name: Tonatiuh
target.bio: Sun god, protector of the warriors and symbolized by the eagle, he presides the fifth (and actual) world age. The gods sacrificed themselves to create him and men has to give him enough energy, through blood, to battle against darkness.

source.name: Ilamacihuatl
source.bio: Lady of Creation. Goddess of weavers, her roar signalled war. She's the elderly version of Chicomecoatl and associated with earth, death, and the milky way

source.bio: Representation of the great white mountain Iztactepetl, she's a mountain goddess, guardian of animals needed for food. Mexica affected by blindness would worship her.

target.name: Tlaloque
target.bio: Minor water-rain gods and servants of Tlaloc, which brought different kind of rain. They are also associated with mountains.

source.name: Itztapaltotec
source.bio: Minor god of Agriculture and fertility, nagual of Xipe Totec, but also a patron of precious metallurgists. He's probably related to Itztli, who is also depicted as a personified knife.

target.name: Itzpapalotl
target.bio: Aztec goddess of sacrifice, associated with earth and fertility, who rules Tomoanchan, and leader of Cihuateteo and Tzitzimime. Her nahual is the butterfly, a manifestation of the dead souls

source.name: Itztlacoliuhqui
source.bio: Blind god of justice and punishment, associated with stone, cold and obsidian. Associated with night and north, he's a variant of Tezcatllipoca.

target.name: Tlahuizcalpantecuhtli
target.bio: Destructive god of the Morning Star, dawn and east. An aspect of Quetzalcoatl which lives in Mictlan. By way of anecdote, he has the longest name in aztec pantheon.

source.name: Mictlantecuhtli
source.bio: God of death and lord of Mictlan, the main Aztec underworld. Living in complete darkness, he guard the bones of dead people but also babies before their birth.

target.name: Xiuhtecuhtli

target.bio: Blind god of justice and punishment, associated with stone, cold and obsidian. Associated with night and north, he's a variant of Tezcatllipoca.

target.bio: Other name for Metztli. As the god of snails and worms, he failed to sacrifice himself to become the sun and was trasnformed into the moon. Symbol of cowardice.

target.name: Ahuitzotl
target.bio: Mix between an otter, a monkey and a dog. He was feared due to his liking of human flesh, especially nails, eyes and teeth. He used the hand on his tail to drown fishermen.

target.bio: Minor water-rain gods and servants of Tlaloc, which brought different kind of rain. They are also associated with mountains.
